ype":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Represents 20% of endometrial cancers","Develops from endometrial hyperplasia","Shows strong estrogen dependence","Demonstrates well-differentiated histology","Occurs primarily in younger women"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EType II endometrial carcinomas have distinct characteristics that differentiate them from Type I cancers:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepresents 20% of endometrial cancers\u003C/strong\u003E - Type II is less common than Type I\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDevelops from endometrial hyperplasia\u003C/strong\u003E - Type II develops independently of hyperplasia\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EShows strong estrogen dependence\u003C/strong\u003E - Type II is not estrogen-dependent\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDemonstrates well-differentiated histology\u003C/strong\u003E - Type II shows poorly differentiated histology\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOccurs primarily in younger women\u003C/strong\u003E - Type II typically occurs in older, post-menopausal women\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EType II endometrial carcinomas are more aggressive, have a poorer prognosis, and are not preceded by hyperplasia. They typically show serous or clear cell histology and are not responsive to hormonal therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Type II endometrial carcinomas are less common, more aggressive, and not estrogen-dependent","Type II endometrial carcinomas typically occur in older women and have poor prognosis","Type II endometrial carcinomas are not associated with endometrial hyperplasia"],"references":["Restaino S, Paglietti C, Arcieri M, Biasioli A, Della Martina M, Mariuzzi L, Andreetta C, Titone F, Bogani G, Raimondo D, Perelli F, Buda A, Petrillo M, Greco P, Ercoli A, Fanfani F, Scambia G, Driul L, Vizzielli G; The Udine Hospital Gyne